abstract: OTTAWA, Ontario, March 31. -- Sir Charles Tupper, after an interview with the Hon. George E. Foster, Minister of Finance, left this afternoon for Washington, and, it is understood, will be followed in a few days by Mr. Foster. abstract: Justice has again miscarried. The indictments for malfeasance in office against Excise Commissioners Alexander Meakim, Edward T. Fitzpatrick, and Joseph T. abstract: A large sum of money, almost $2,500, was added to the treasury of the Actors' Fund, through the medium of the benefit performance at Palmer's Theatre yesterday afternoon. This is the important point for the Fund, which naturally looks principally to the financial results of the entertainment. To the large audience in attendance, the artistic result was of more importance, and that was of a nature to amply repay every person who attended the performance.

abstract: CHICAGO, April 2. -- The Provision market was a very irregular one to-day. In Pork the market was so limited that rather violent fluctuations, followed either moderate purchases or moderate sales. The news was of both sorts. abstract: ALBANY, N.Y., April 3. -- The third storm this year to cripple the telegraph and telephone service in this vicinity prevailed here last night and to-day. It proved more disastrous to wires than either of its predecessors. Nearly a foot of soggy snow fell, and as a result whole lines of telephone wires were prostrated. In some streets poles carrying from 200 to 300 wires broke, dragging the tangle of wires to the street.

abstract: LONG BRANCH, N.J., April 3. -- The storm last night did considerable damage along the New-Jersey coast. The temporary bulkhead at Sandt's Octagon House at Seabright was all torn out and the sea is now up to the hotel plazza. The gaps in the bluff here were enlarged. Only slight damage was done at Asbury Park, but a number of bulkheads at Monmouth Beach were badly damaged.

abstract: OTTAWA, Ontario, April 4. -- Contrary to expectation, the negotiations for closer trade relations between Canada and the United States have advanced another stage. Sir John Macdonald in an interview this afternoon expressed himself as confident of the result. The delay of Sir Charles Tupper in starting for Washington, coupled with the apparent apathy of Secretary Blaine, augured unfavorably for the Dominion Government.

abstract: CHICAGO, April 4. -- Two theatrical productions new to Chicago have been given here this week, and both came heralded as "metropolitan successes." abstract: NEWPORT, R.I., April 9. -- The court of inquiry into the loss of the United States tug Triana at Cuttyhunk is still in progress at the United States torpedo station. Superintendent Kimball of the life-saving service is in attendance, as the cause of the accident is understood to be connected with the life-saving service.

abstract: ALBANY, April 9. -- Gov. Hill has begun to put his canal machine in shape for next Fall's campaign. abstract: Some time ago Sir Reginald Barnwell, an English Baronet, visiting this country, directed his correspondents to send his mail to the general delivery at Baltimore. abstract: LONDON, April 12. -- Money was easy early in the week, but tightened on successive withdrawals of gold for Germany, amounting to 450,000, together with 200,000 going on Monday. The Last Bank of England returns of diminished reserve, combined with the effinx of bullion abroad, renders an early advance of the bank rate exceedingly probable. Discount hardened during the week and was quoted at 2 1/2 for three months and 2 for short.

abstract: The Brooklyn Aldermen refused point blank yesterday to put up at public auction the franchise for laying conduits through which to supply houses, markets, and office buildings with cold air. This franchise was granted to ex-Sheriff Rhinehart and John Guilfoyle a week ago, and not a cent was asked for it. Then Lawyer Butcher, on behalf of a rival refrigerating company, waited on Mayor Chapin and told him that the franchise was worth $100,000.

abstract: LONDON, April 13. -- Ten thousand of the striking miners assembled to-day to protest against the action of the authorities in prohibiting a meeting which had been planned. The police attempted to disperse them, and met with so stubborn a resistance that the military were summoned. Even then the strikers were dispersed with difficulty, many of all concerned in the riot being injured. About a score of the rioters' leaders were arrested.

abstract: ALBANY, April 14. -- The far-famed New-York Giants had to lower their colors to-day. They made a gallant struggle, however, but defeat was inevitable, and they were forced to succumb to it. abstract: " Brannigan's Morgue" will probably not be the new home of the Sixth Judicial District Court. The court is now at Eighteenth Street and Fourth Avenue, but will have to move May 1. abstract: CHICAGO, April 14. -- The Provision market had the announcement from the yards that Hogs were 10@ 15c higher. Nobody was surprised when product started off at something of an advance. The market proved a dull one. At the close all sorts of product was exactly were it was Monday night. July Pork opened at $13.20 and closed at $13.10, July Lard at $7.17, closed at $7.15; July Ribsat $6.70 and closed at $6.62.

abstract: ALBANY, April 15. -- In the language of the baseball enthusiast, the Albanys were not in it to-day. abstract: TROY, April 16. -- After a close and interesting game the New-Yorks were forced to lower their colors to-day to the Troy Club. The defeat was due to the skillful pitching of McGuire and Shea. They handle the ball with rare skill, allowing the New-Yorkers to make only half a dozen hits. On the other hand, Rusie and John Ewing were touched up pretty lively, the Troys scoring 10, with a total of 18 hits.

abstract: Cleopatra's Needle is decaying and will soon be nothing but a shapeless stone. We are now told that this is not the result of the London atmosphere, but that the granite was already disintegrating before it left Egypt. I doubt this. The needle existed without disintegration for several thousand years on the Nile, and, if it had been left there, it probably would have existed for many other thousands of years.

abstract: WALLHALLA, S.C., April 19. -- This pleasant little town is the gateway to the Southern mountain region. abstract: BUFFALO, April 20. -- One of the prettiest games of ball seen in this vicinity for some years was the contest to-day between the Giants and the reorganized Buffalo Club. From start to finish it was anybody's game, and not until the last man was retired in the ninth inning could the winner be picked. Over 2,000 persons witnessed the struggle, and their joy knew no bounds when the Bisons won the game.

abstract: SCOTTDALE, Penn., April 20. -- To-day was prolific of excitement and small riots throughout the region. The women generally are leading and most bitter in their attacks on the deputies. Heretofore they have been silent, but when evictors attacked their homes the foreign women especially were driven wild. During several squabbles to-day a couple of deputies were struck with stones and one was out on the arm while pushing his way through a crowd.

abstract: BOSTON, April 21. -- The schooner James H. Woodhouse of Boston, Capt. Kelly, which left Boston Jan. 30 for San Domingo, arrived here at 8 P.M. in tow of the tug Elsie. Capt. The Woodhouse was dismasted, and had been drifting around the past three months under jury masts.

abstract: The date set for the final adjournment of the Legislature falls on Thursday next. abstract: CONNELLSVILLE, Penn., April 27. -- The coke strikers were in high glee to-day over propositions from Isaac Taylor and B.F. Keister  Co., operating 900 ovens, for a conference looking to a resumption of work at last year's prices. The United Mine Workers' officials will assent to the conference and endeavor to secure a resumption of work forthwith. The Frick and McClure Companies, the two largest in the region, however, show no indication of yielding.

abstract: HARTFORD, April 27. -- The Senate this afternoon reinstated Gen. abstract: John W. Devine, a lineman in the employ of the Metropolitan Telephone and Telegraph Company, met with a horrible death yesterday morning while at work on a pole in front of 270 Fourth Avenue, near Twenty-first Street, removing dead wires. A wire which he was cutting came in contact with an electric-light wire, and he received a shock and fell headlong from the pole to the sidewalk and was picked up dead.

abstract: The lively operetta by John Strauss was revived last evening in German at the Amberg Theatre. That stand-by, Carl Streitmann, enjoyed a benefit, accompanied with many architectural efforts of the florist and with applause and recalls galore.
